<br>
In my opinion, good poetry takes a little analysation and requires you to scratch at the surface to get to the message it is putting across. It's also nice when it has a proper structure, i.e. iambic pentameter. But then, the only poem that has ever made me vaguely emotional was by Philip Larkin. It's called <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Talking in Bed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. It was the first time I had read a piece of poetry and felt absolute despair by the end of it:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Talking in bed ought to be easiest,<br>
Lying together there goes back so far,<br>
An emblem of two people being honest.<br>
<br>
Yet more and more time passes silently.<br>
Outside, the wind's incomplete unrest<br>
Builds and disperses clouds about the sky,<br>
<br>
And dark towns heap up on the horizon.<br>
None of this cares for us. Nothing shows why<br>
At this unique distance from isolation<br>
<br>
It becomes still more difficult to find<br>
Words at once true and kind,<br>
Or not untrue and not unkind.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I cried the first time I read it, and it still gets a response from me every time I read it. Though at the time it didn't strike a personal note for me (I had never been through the breakdown of a relationship when I first read it), its message was so bleak that it played on my mind for days. <br>
<br>
I do not expect everyone who writes a poem to write like a professional. However, putting your work up on the internet for everyone to see is akin to having it published. Some will like it and others won't. As long as people don't attack one another for their opinions, there shouldn't be a problem.<br>
<br>
